# UI Authoring Runtime Boundary

- Author persistent UI structure with UI Toolkit UXML, `UIDocument`, and USS; do not build large persistent panel/row hierarchies imperatively at runtime.
- Runtime template cloning is allowed for repeated rows, cards, list items, and feature-owned dynamic content; clone, bind, and cache instead of rebuilding the whole screen.
- Screen, view, presenter, and controller classes should keep clear boundaries: `View` owns `VisualElement` references and UI Toolkit callbacks, while plain C# `Presenter`/`Controller` orchestrates view models and use case calls.
- If UI `*Controller : MonoBehaviour` classes grow, move UI Toolkit boundary code into `*View` and service/use case orchestration into a plain C# `*Controller` or `*Presenter`.
- Runtime code should only perform data bind, state refresh, class toggles, visibility/tween, and input emission; do not add gameplay decisions or price/economy rules there.
- If UI runtime reads config, use it for display text, icons, colors, ordering, or layout; purchase/reward/price decisions belong to a use case or application service.
- When a new UI feature adds runtime behavior or presenter logic, add presenter-level tests first, then change `UIDocument`/scene wiring.
- UI text/color/icon keys should be stable IDs or config; do not bind behavior to hierarchy indexes or sibling order.

## Example

```csharp
// BAD: Runtime builds the whole screen and adds a business rule.
if (playerLevel > 3)
{
    root.Add(CreateUpgradePanel());
    _gameState.Money -= 100;
}

// GOOD: UXML owns structure; runtime only binds view data and emits intent.
var viewModel = _upgradePresenter.BuildLayout(_gameState, _pricingConfig);
_upgradeView.Apply(viewModel);
```
